social_posts.post_text: Lunch today was so good and easy and delicious I had to share— leftover short grain sweet + brown rice. Steamed to reheat (this is the best way to reheat sticky textured rice) topped with tamari and furikake with bee pollen which is surprising and delicious (from Dark Horse Organic) Steamed local carrots and cabbage, 6 minute egg, kraut and some avo plus plenty of olive oil and flakey sea salt. Xo

I changed up the holiday brittle this year and wanted to let you know incase you’re still looking for something fun to make. 

So instead of adding chocolate to the mix (which means it’s hard to stop it melting with the warm brown rice syrup) I left it out and dipped shards of brittle in dark chocolate. I also tried drizzling it over. In this picture you see crushed dehydrated cranberries that I made for some tree decorating. 

I also tried rolling out the brittle between parchment paper to get flat pieces for dipping. Be sure to keep it thin otherwise you may over bake it like I did with a tray. 
It’s also saltier and I chose cherries and pistachios for a change and I really love the look and flavor. 
✨✨✨Happy solstice ✨✨✨

HOLIDAY BRITTLE VERSION 2

1 cup large flaked coconut 
1 cup pumpkin seeds, toasted ( try and get Austrian)
1/2 cup pistachios, mostly left whole
1/2 cup toasted whole almonds, chopped
1/2 cup raw walnuts (I use halves), chopped
1/2 cup raw pecan halves ( I use halves), chopped 
1/2 cup dried cherries, chopped
2 teaspoons flaked sea salt
1/2 cup brown rice syrup ( no you can’t use anything to replace)
2 Tablespoons raw cashew butter
Zest of one orange 
1 teaspoon Vanilla extract
1 bar dark chocolate, melted in double boiler

Preheat oven to 350 F. 
Add coconut, pumpkin seeds, pistachios almonds, walnuts, pecans, cherries and salt to a medium bowl and toss well to combine. 

Warm brown rice syrup in a small pot until bubbling. Remove from heat and add cashew butter, orange zest and vanilla, and whisk until smooth. Pour into bowl and stir with a rubber spatula to combine. 

Crumble over a sheet of parchment papered ( the size of a 1/2 sheet pan) cover with another sheet and roll out until about 1/4 inch thick. Remove top sheet and bake for 8 minutes.

Winter cranberry tonic with schisandra— it’s so juicy, tart, warming and delicious that I have to share the recipe. 

This makes a very strong brew—which is why I’m calling it a tonic. You can add half boiling water or more for a weaker tea. Add honey if you like. 

6 cups filtered water
2 cups frozen cranberries
3 tablespoons schisandra berries *
1 orange, cut up

Bring to a boil. Lower heat and simmer for 10 minutes (covered or not) then let cool in pot. Strain and press of the cranberries etc to release as much liquid as possible. Pour into a jar and store in the fridge. Drink warm or cold after diluting. 
Makes about 4 1/2 cups. 
Not sure how long it lasts…yet! 

*you can order schisandra berries @rishitea

Here’s the recipe for the Strawberry, rose and Earl Grey muffins I made last weekend. They’re so tender and fragrant and even though they don’t contain chocolate I think they’re perfect for Valentine’s Day ♥️🍓🌹🫖🥀

4 teaspoons lavender Earl grey tea I used @rishitea 
1 tablespoon dried rose buds
1/2 cup + 2 tablespoons almond milk (homemade is always best) 
1 cup almond flour
1/2 cup oat flour
1/2 cup brown rice flour
2 teaspoons baking powder
2 eggs, beaten
1/3 cup melted ghee —I use @goddess.ghee or coconut or olive oil or a combination
1/4 cup fresh orange juice 
1/4 cup maple syrup
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
1/2 teaspoon sea salt 
1 1/2 cups sliced strawberries (I used frozen) defrost a little to slice. 

Preheat oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit. Line 10 muffin cups and set aside. 

Add tea, rose and almond milk to a small pot and bring to a simmer. Cover pot, remove from heat and steep 15 mins. 

In a medium bowl combine almond flour, oat flour, brown rice flour and baking powder. Use a whisk to break up any lumps. 

In another bowl combine eggs, ghee (make sure it’s not hot), orange juice, maple, vanilla and salt. Strain in the steeped almond milk, pressing out as much liquid as possible. Whisk to combine, pour into flour mixture and gently stir. When almost combined fold in strawberries being careful not to over mix. Scoop into lined muffin pan and bake 30-35 mins or until a tooth pick inserted in the center comes out clean. 
Allow to cool for 10 mins in pan then remove and cool on a rack.

I love this houjicha banana bread recipe made with houjicha powder from @rishitea Houjicha is powdered form has an earthy rich and almost chocolatey flavor that goes so well with banana and walnuts—it also gives you a nice little buzz if that’s what you’re into. 

This bread is gluten free and dairy free but delicious with butter. 

You can find the recipe here: 

https://journal.rishi-tea.com/houjicha-banana-walnut-bread/

Use my code AMYCHAPLIN for a discount when buying tea. 

Can’t wait to hear what you think of the bread. ♥️

If you fancy an houjicha latte find my recipe in highlights Xo

Here’s some refreshing matcha popsicles for these sultry late summer days. I developed this recipe using my favorite @rishitea matcha tea blended with coconut milk and almond milk and a banana— which creates the perfect creamy texture. Just be sure the banana isn’t too ripe as you don’t want it to over power the tea. I’ll link the recipe in stories. 💚

Here’s the recipe: 
This is @lizprueitt_tartine version of @alicemedrich Fruit and nut cake with the small changes I made. It’s such a good recipe and a great way to use up all your dried fruit and nuts in one go. I will say I think pecans and walnuts are definitely good to include—if I’d had chestnuts like Liz used I would have added them. Liz also suggests to give very dried out fruit a quick soak in boiling water which I did with the figs and cherries and then added a splash of the soaking liquid. 

I cut the sugar in half and used coconut sugar— which makes it look a bit darker. Honestly I’d cut it out completely but was worried about the volume. One thing to note is that you will swear there isn’t enough cake batter when mixing but there is— even with half the sugar. 

I happened to have tapioca flour so not sure what would happen if you replaced it with arrowroot. Weigh in if you have thoughts on this. 

Been loving this cut thin with butter and a cup of tea then realized that of course ghee (🙏 @goddess.ghee ) is perfect for it—especially since there is not oil in the recipe. I love that nothing is chopped— I did chop the candied ginger though because it’s so sweet and strong. 

Combine:
250 grams soaked and drained figs, prunes and pineapple or any dried fruit 
250 grams raisins/sultanas, dried cherries, dried cranberries, chopped candied ginger (about a handful)
Set aside:
250 grams raw walnuts, pecans, pistachios and hazelnuts 

In a large bowl combine:
40 grams oat flour
40 grams tapioca starch
75 grams coconut sugar 
1/4 tsp baking powder
1/4 tsp baking soda 
1 tsp fine salt I used @capbeautydaily pink mountain salt 
Add:
Zest of one orange 
3 eggs 
Mix well then stir in dried fruit and nuts until coated with batter. Heat oven to 300 degrees F. Pour into a lined loaf pan and bake for 1 hour until batter is cooked. I cooked mine for an extra 10 minutes. 
You can bake in small loaf pans too if you like it. Happy winter ❄️ 🌲🤍
